Both are great podcasts. They do not overlap that much stylistically, which is great to have diverse formats among the big names. 

*Theo*
Sincere, introspective, emphatetic. Unorthodox and refreshing perspectives. Great storyteller and listener. Innate ability to read the mood of the room and adapt accordingly.  
His podcast is much more reciprocal than JRE, due to his curious nature and his puzzling ability to conjure novel thoughts and sentences spontaneously. His podcasts are more light-hearted, non-confrontational, shorter format, with a more freestyle structure.

*Joe*
Investigative, open-minded, conversationalist. Huge catalog  with non-discriminatory admission, you'll find an episode of any topic. 
Great mediator; he's not afraid to confront guests with hard and abrasive questions, regardless of the guest's reknown, but he will almost always let the guests  speak their mind. Has broad knowledge of many topics, making his podcast beyond- surface intellectually. He also posess this juvenile curiosity, but grounded in common sense, which makes him a great interviewer; being engaged and asking reasonable questions.

His long retained non-conformity to the establishment,  supersedes the role of his podcast to a larger role as an mainstream alt-news media. Its place in the media is indispensible; firstly, due to it's long format being a podcast, opens up more nuance and in-depth view on guests, in which you elsewhere most have heard in an 3 min interview. And his "neutrality" of guests who's coming on the podcast. Having access to a long podcast which provide insight in things you disagree with, but discover that it isn't so binary as you assumed.
